<paragraph blockId="27.[264,672,1004,1065]" box="[264,401,1039,1065]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<figureCitation box="[264,401,1039,1065]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="28.[264,368,1804,1828]" captionTargetBox="[369,1231,676,1786]" captionTargetId="figure-145@28.[349,1238,670,1794]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 13. Alterosa fluminensis, new species. Male genitalia: 13A—lateral view; 13B—dorsal view of segments IX and X; 13C—inferior appendage, dorsal view; 13D—phallic apparatus, lateral view; 13E—phallic apparatus, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5046314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5046314/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 13A–E</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[264,1324,1119,1905]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[563,749,1119,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="escova">
<emphasis box="[563,749,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Alterosa escova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[763,851,1119,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flinti">
<emphasis box="[763,851,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. flinti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Almeida &amp; Duarte" authorityYear="2003" box="[866,1015,1119,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Dolophilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marinonii">
<emphasis box="[866,1015,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. marinonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[1072,1278,1119,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanctaeteresae">
<emphasis box="[1072,1278,1119,1144]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. sanctaeteresae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, all of which have similarly developed inferior appendages and highly modified and enlarged preanal appendages armed with spine­like setae. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[936,1026,1199,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flinti">
<emphasis box="[936,1026,1199,1224]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. flinti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[1088,1296,1199,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanctaeteresae">
<emphasis box="[1088,1296,1199,1224]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. sanctaeteresae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs in lacking elongate, apically setose lateral branches from the intermediate appendages. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[411,525,1279,1304]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="escova">
<emphasis box="[411,525,1279,1304]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. escova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Almeida &amp; Duarte" authorityYear="2003" box="[583,732,1279,1304]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Dolophilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marinonii">
<emphasis box="[583,732,1279,1304]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. marinonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs in the shape and armature of the preanal appendage, which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[517,685,1319,1344]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fluminensis">
<emphasis box="[517,685,1319,1344]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">A. fluminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
possesses a basal pad with elongate, stalked setae, in addition to apical and mesolateral setae. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2005" box="[750,989,1359,1384]" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Alterosa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fluminensis">
<emphasis box="[750,989,1359,1384]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Alterosa fluminensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also unique in possessing a small, stalked basal process at the base of tergum X, although the latter structure may not always be present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[264,1324,1119,1905]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Adult. Color overall, dark brown; legs, palps and antennae slightly paler, wings irregularly mottled with small light brown spots. Male forewing 
<quantity box="[974,1097,1519,1545]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.2" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="5.6" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.2">5.2–6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[264,1324,1119,1905]" lastBlockId="28.[264,1323,284,590]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Male genitalia. Tergum VIII with posteromesal margin not or scarcely emarginate. Sternum IX with anterolateral margin broadly rounded; posteroventral margin greatly produced, extending sinuously from dorsum; tergum IX reduced, forming a mesal projection over base of tergum X, mesal projection extending into short mesal stalk, terminating with small bulbous, apically setose process (stalked process broken in 
<typeStatus box="[1046,1148,1719,1745]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">holotype</typeStatus>
specimen, but present with specimen; apparently undeveloped in 
<typeStatus box="[860,961,1759,1785]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">paratype</typeStatus>
specimen). Tergum X tapered from base, in lateral profile undulate; apex sensillate, subacute as viewed dorsally, rounded and slightly enlarged in lateral view. Intermediate appendage heavily sclerotized, moderately elongate, spine­like; apex acute. Preanal appendage greatly enlarged, broad basally, elongate, with short, stout setae apically, extending along ventromesal margin; apex rounded; preanal appendage basally with flange­like process bearing cluster of prominent, stalked, spine­like setae, flange­like process small, rounded, more or less ventral and mesal to appendage itself. Inferior appendages robust; 1st article, in lateral view, short, nearly as wide as long, bulging mesally; 2nd article longer than 1st article, relatively broad and nearly uniform in width; apex rounded, with prominent pad of short, stiff apicomesal setae. Phallobase tubular, relatively short, narrow basally, expanded apically, rather sharply bent at midlength; endotheca with numerous short tack­like spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
